chunks.text:
return delivers the value to the exact spot of the call, where the program can catch and reuse it. Worked example:
def add(a, b):
    return a + b
total = add(2, 3) puts 5 into total, and print(total * 10) shows 50. A returned value that nothing catches — a bare add(2, 3) line — is computed and silently discarded.

return ends the function the instant it executes — lines after an executed return never run. Worked example:
def status():
    return "done"
    print("never shown")
print(status()) prints done and nothing else. A function may contain several returns, but each call executes at most one: the first reached wins.

The early-return pattern: handle the special case first and exit immediately, then write the normal case below with no else. Worked example:
def ticket_price(age):
    if age < 5:
        return 0
    return 10
ticket_price(3) returns 0 at the door; ticket_price(30) skips the if and returns 10. The code reads top to bottom: special case out of the way, normal case in a straight line.
